\end{document}
```

### Scala Code Example

Here's a basic example of how you might start processing data using Scala and Spark:

```scala
import org.apache.spark.sql.SparkSession
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions._

object SeaLevelAnalysis {
  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
    val spark = SparkSession.builder
      .appName("Sea Level Analysis")
      .config("spark.master", "local")
      .getOrCreate()

    // Load sea level data
    val seaLevelData = spark.read.option("header", "true").csv("path/to/sea_level_data.csv")

    // Data preprocessing
    val cleanData = seaLevelData
      .na.drop()
      .withColumn("SeaLevel", col("SeaLevel").cast("double"))

    // Perform analysis
    cleanData.describe().show()

    // Further analysis and modeling here...

    spark.stop()
  }
}
```

This Scala code initializes a Spark session, loads the sea level data, performs basic preprocessing, and provides a starting point for further analysis. 

By incorporating additional data sources, you can enhance your understanding and develop more comprehensive models to address the challenges posed by sea level rise due to climate change.
